# Imputing missing values in Income based on education and marital status

marketing_data['Income'] = marketing_data.groupby(['Marital_Status', 'Education'])['Income'].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.mean()))

Assumption: Customers with similar education and marital status make the same yearly income, on average.

We see that there are a number of outliers that are causing skewness (right tail) across most of the features. Hence we need to perform Outlier treatment.

Outlier Treatment¶

In [ ]:
from feature_engine.outliers import Winsorizer

capper = Winsorizer(capping_method='iqr', tail='both', fold=1.5, variables=numerical_features_exclBinary)
marketing_data_no_outliers = capper.fit_transform(marketing_data)

Outlier treatment completed

# Ordinal Encoder

Ordinal encoder replaces categories with digits:

  1. Arbitrary
  • Arbitrarily assigns 0, 1, 2..
  1. Ordered
  • computes avg. of each category
  • sort in ascending order
  • assigns 0, 1, 2..

Hypothesis Testing¶

Before beginning with Hypothesis testing, we need to run an Anderson-Darling test in order to check for normality (Gaussian distribution) of our features. This will help us determine:

  • Are our features normally distributed
  • If not, do they need variance stabilizing transformations to make them normally distributed
  • Which test should be used for Hypothesis testing (T-test, Anova, Chi-Square)
In [ ]:
for column in ['Income', 'Total_Children','Age','Total_Spending']:
    result = stats.anderson(marketing_data_encoded[column], dist='norm')
    print('\n\n',f'Column: \033[1m {column} \033[0m - Statistic: {result.statistic:.3f}')
    plt.figure(figsize=(4,2))
    sns.kdeplot(marketing_data_encoded[column])
    plt.show()

    # Interpreting the result
    for i in range(len(result.critical_values)):
        sl, cv = result.significance_level[i], result.critical_values[i]
        if result.statistic < cv:
            print(f'{column} - {sl}%: Gaussian (fail to reject H0)')
        else:
            print(f'{column} - {sl}%: Not Gaussian (reject H0)')

Since all the numerical continuous features are not normally distributed, we need to tranform the data using variance stabilizing transformations to try and achieve normality. This is in order to be able to use T-test, Anova & Chi-square tests. If we fail to achieve normality after transformation, we will have to go for the Non-parametric tests for hypothesis.

Hypothesis 1: Older people are not as tech-savvy and probably prefer shopping in-store.¶

In [ ]:
# Null Hypothesis (H0): Older people have no preferred shopping method.
# Alternate Hypothesis: Older people prefer shopping in-store.

# Defining the 2 groups to be compared

older_ppl_group = marketing_data_encoded[marketing_data_encoded['Age']>50]
younger_ppl_group = marketing_data_encoded[marketing_data_encoded['Age']<=50]

from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu # mann whitney u is like T-test

ustat, p_val = mannwhitneyu(older_ppl_group['NumStorePurchases'], younger_ppl_group['NumStorePurchases'])
print(p_val)

7.751984585643394e-09

Technical Interpretation: A low p-value suggests that there is a statistically significant preferred shopping method among older people.

Non-Technical Interpretation: Older people's purchase history indicates that they might not feel the same purchasing across the 3 channels, with shopping in-store preferred over others.

From above p-val (< 0.05) we have sufficient evidence to reject the Null hypotheses that Older people have no preferred shopping method.

  • We infer that Older people are indeed not tech-savvy and prefer shopping in-store.

Hypothesis 2: Customers with kids probably have less time to visit a store and would prefer to shop online.¶

In [ ]:
# Null Hypothesis (H0): Customers with kids have no preferred shopping method.
# Alternate Hypothesis: Customers with kids prefer shopping online.

# Defining the 2 groups to be compared

Cust_with_kids = marketing_data_encoded[marketing_data_encoded['Total_Children']>0]
Cust_without_kids = marketing_data_encoded[marketing_data_encoded['Total_Children']==0]

from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu

ustat, p_val = mannwhitneyu(Cust_with_kids['NumWebPurchases'], Cust_without_kids['NumWebPurchases'])
print(p_val)

4.1341095294624224e-08

Technical Interpretation: A low p-value suggests that there is a statistically significant preferred shopping method among customers with kids.

Non-Technical Interpretation: The purchase history of customers with kids indicates that they might not feel the same purchasing across the 3 channels, with shopping online preferred over others.

From above p_val (< 0.05) we have sufficient evidence to reject the Null hypotheses that Customers with kids have no preferred shopping method.

  • We infer that Customers with kids indeed have less time to visit a store and prefer shopping online.

Hypothesis 3: Other distribution channels may cannibalize sales at the store.¶

In [ ]:
# Null Hypothesis (H0): Other distribution channels have no effect on sales at the store.
# Alternate Hypothesis: Other distribution channels cannibalize sales at the store.

# Defining the 2 groups to be compared

Other_dist_channels = marketing_data_encoded['NumWebPurchases'] + marketing_data_encoded['NumCatalogPurchases']
Store_dist_channel = marketing_data_encoded['NumStorePurchases']

from scipy.stats import mannwhitneyu

ustat, p_val = mannwhitneyu(Other_dist_channels, Store_dist_channel)
print(p_val)

0.0003198001700288095

Technical Interpretation: A low p-value (<0.05) suggests that there is a statistically significant effect of other distribution channels.

Non-Technical Interpretation: The online and catalog purchase history indicates that they are the preferred shopping method among customers, which may lead to cannibalizing sales at the store.

From above p_val (< 0.05) we have sufficient evidence to reject the Null hypotheses that Other distribution channels have no effect on sales at the store.

  • We infer that Other distribution channels indeed cannibalize sales at the store.

Hypothesis 4: Does the US fare significantly better than the rest of the world in terms of total purchases?¶

In [ ]:
# Null Hypothesis (H0): Total purchases from the US are same as the rest of the world.
# Alternate Hypothesis: Total purchases from the US are significantly better than the rest of the world.

# Defining the 2 groups to be compared

US = marketing_data_no_outliers[marketing_data_no_outliers['Country'] == 'US']
Rest_of_World = marketing_data_no_outliers[marketing_data_no_outliers['Country'] != 'US']

from scipy.stats import kruskal # kruskal wallis is like 1 way Anova (1 independednt var)
stat, p_val = kruskal(US['Total_Purchases'], Rest_of_World['Total_Purchases'] )
print(p_val)

0.14199931791819556

Technical Interpretation: A high p-value (>0.05) suggests that there is no statistically significant difference in total purchases from the US as compared to the rest of the world.

Non-Technical Interpretation: The total purchases from the US are similar to those from the rest of the world; US does not fare significantly better.

From above p_val (> 0.05) we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the Null hypotheses that Total purchases from the US are same as the rest of the world.

  • We infer that The US does NOT fare significantly better than the rest of the world in terms of total purchases

Insights

  • Last Campaign: We see that during the last campaign, there is a huge spike in acceptance among Middle Age customers; acceptance rate doubles in the last campaign for Middle Age customers. Acceptance rate among other age groups is marginally higher compared to other campigns.

Comparing with the other campaigns:

  • 1st Campaign: Acceptance rate among Middle Age & Senior Citizen is higher
  • 2nd Campaign: Customers accepting offers dips considerably across all age groups; no offer accepted by the Elderly
  • 3rd Campaign: Acceptance spikes among the Middle Age group
  • 4th Campaign: Acceptance amonth Senior Citizens increases and is on par with Young Adults
  • 5th Campaign: Increased acceptance among Young Adults.

        plot=sns.barplot(data=data[i],x='Campaign', y='No. of Customers',  ax=axes[i], palette=colors)
#         if i<4: axes[i].legend_.remove()
        plt.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.3,1))
        sns.despine(top=True, right=True)
        axes[i].set_xlabel('' )
        axes[i].set_ylabel('')
        axes[i].set_title(titles[i])
        axes[i].set_xticklabels(axes[i].get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
        plot.set_ylim(0, 180)


plt.tight_layout()
